text: So when I joined in 2003, that was during, I'd say, the early days of that build out. And a lot of those early years, one area of intense focus was quant macro. That was something that I was involved in building out a diversified set of macro signals in the 2000s. Parallel to that, we started trading quant equity strategies in 2001. And the initial focus there was stat arb. That was actually around the time that we first launched the Absolute Return Program, was in 2002, to be that mix of managed futures plus cash equities. And then actually around 2009, that was the next phase where we started making a push into short-term trading. And we can get into more what that means. But for us, that's intraday data, statistical models with about a one-week holding period. By the early 2000s, let's say the firm had put in a great deal of effort in building out this set of diversified strategies well beyond trend. At that point, we really had, I'd say, four major styles that we still have today, which would be quant macro, short-term, trend, and equity market neutral. But in the early 2010s, most of Campbell's A-U M was still kind of heavily tilted towards trend-heavy managed futures. And even the car portfolio, in terms of its risk allocation, was heavily tilted towards trend. It was about 60% trend at that point. So we took a look at essentially all of the work we'd done and what that had resulted in in terms of this diversified set of models, and then matched that against the risk allocation and said, there seems to be an opportunity here. So it was in the summer of 2014 that we actually made a strategic shift in the allocation within car to be roughly equally balanced between those four. So we're investing in the car portfolio, and then we moved to the car portfolio in And then we moved to the car portfolio in 2014. And that was in terms of the overall market, which was the market that we really wanted So we had a lot of really strong returns on a relative basis compared to a lot of the peers, really well-managed risk management and the diversification we're looking for versus traditional assets. So that gave us the conviction that that was the right direction to go in, and subsequently we moved even our managed futures portfolio to a more balanced mix of the strategies within that. David Steinberger, F&O Capital, Inc.: The other pieces that we've continued to build out the strategy since that time. So in a given year, we typically add a lot of risk to the portfolio. So we've added about five to 10 new models to the portfolio, and that's what gets us to about 130 alphas in car today.
